				<p>
					An average person can utilize a Cloud Computer (Virtual Desktop) in their day to day life if one is doing any kind of hardware-						intensive work. Virtual Desktops are a cheap solution instead of purchasing a full-time workstation PC. It can be used for personal 					use as well as for business use, most of the services that are provided by companies as of 2020 provide more plans and services for 					businesses, but there are a few companies that provide Virtual Desktops for personal use. 
				</p>
				
				
				<p>
					There are multiple ways a person can avail Cloud Computing services (Virtual Desktops) online, a few of the services that I have found 						convincing are listed below: 
				</p>
				<ol>
					<li>Paperspace 
						<ul>
							<li>
								Paperspace is one of the best services that one can avail for personal use, if one needs a virtual desktop for personal 								use Paperspace offers plans which are cheap and provide high-performance virtual desktops for cheap. Paperspace doesn’t 								have as many datacenters as the other companies on the list, but Paperspace is still a very viable option for personal 								   computing.
							</li>
						</ul>
					</li>
					<li>AWS Workspace (Amazon Web Services Workspace) 
						<ul>
							<li>
								AWS is a cloud computing service for amazon which includes workspaces, workspaces are an enterprise-level solution for 								  virtual desktops, which can be used for personal use as well as enterprise use. AWS offers several plans including a 									free trial to try whether or not you like their service.
							</li>
						</ul>
					</li>
					<li>Microsoft Azure
						<ul>
							<li>
								This is another cloud-based service but this time it is provided by Microsoft, Azure is meant for enterprise-level 									virtualization, but can be used by an average person as well as it provides a few personal plans for relatively low 								prices. Microsoft Azure also has more data centers compare to AWS or Paperspace, which will allow for lower latency 								compared to other services.
							</li>
						</ul>
					</li>
				</ol>
				<p>
					The companies that are listed above are one of the few that support Cloud Computer (Virtual Desktops), there are many more that 					support cloud computing and there may be another preference in your particular area.
				</p>
				<p>
					To wrap it all off, I would like to say cloud computing isn’t that new a technology but is certainly on the rise in recent years 					and I believe the COVID-19 pandemic has given it the perfect platform to be a viable choice for startups, enterprises, companies, 					and personal use.
